<note xml:id="ch36n124"><p id="ch36n124pa1">Our knowledge of these mercenaries, who subverted the Western empire, is derived from Procopius (de Bell. Gothico, l. i. c. i. p. 308). The popular opinion and the recent historians represent Odoacer in the false light of a <hi rend="italic">stranger</hi> and a <hi rend="italic">king,</hi> who invaded Italy with an army of foreigners, his native subjects.</p></note>

<note xml:id="ch36n125"><p id="ch36n125pa1">Orestes, qui eo tempore quando Attila ad Italiam venit se illi junxit, et ejus notarius factus fuerat. Anonym. Vales. p. 716 [8,  38]. He is mistaken in the date; but we may credit his assertion that the secretary of Attila was the father of Augustulus.</p></note>

<note xml:id="ch36n125a"><p id="ch36n125apa1">[The quarto has the misprint <hi rend="italic">Epiphanites,</hi> which has remained uncorrected in subsequent editions.]</p></note>

