<note xml:id="ch37n127"><p id="ch37n127pa1">Justinian, Codex, l. i. tit. xxvii. [1]. Marcellin. in Chron. p. 45, in Thesaur. Temporum Scaliger [ad. ann. 484; ed. Mommsen, p. 93]. Procopius, de Bell. Vandal. l. i. c. 7, p. 196. Gregor. Magnus. Dialog. iii. 32. None of these witnesses have specified the number of the confessors, which is fixed at sixty in an old menology (apud Ruinart, p. 486). Two of them lost their speech by fornication; but the miracle is enhanced by the singular instance of a boy who had <hi rend="italic">never</hi> spoken before his tongue was cut out. [The miracle of Tipasa has been recently defended by the Jesuit Count Paul von Hoensbroech (1889), but the evidence has been criticised and rejected by Grres in the Zeitschrift fr wissenschaftliche Theologie, 36, p. 494 <hi rend="italic">sqq.,</hi> 1894. It is amusing to observe that Grres imagines that Gibbon, for once credulous, accepts the miracle of Tipasa!]</p></note>

